      "answer": "Nitrogen (N) is typically deficient first in yellowing lower leaves due to mobility limitations when mixed with heavy clay holding water/nutrients poorly. Apply composted manure or well-aged cow manure, as they provide slow-release N that benefits plants without burning roots quickly enough for immediate over-correction.",
      "rubric": "- Correctly identifies Nitrogen (N) from symptom/soil interaction logic.\n- Recommends a specific organic amendment appropriate for container clay soil.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "**Scenario:** Your pepper plants have pale green new growth and small leaves, but your tomato plant has strong stems yet reddish-purple undersides of older leaves.\n**Task:** Construct the distinct NPK profiles (high/med/low) for each plant based on these specific physiological symptoms. Explain why one needs Phosphorus more than Nitrogen.",
      "answer": "Pepper: High N, Low P (symptoms indicate general nitrogen deficiency affecting new growth size/color). Tomato: Med/Low N, High P or Balanced but low K actually points to Magnesium/Phosphate issues showing in older leaves via translocation; however, standard NPK interpretation for purple undersides often indicates Phosphorus demand if root uptake is the issue, while Nitrogen mobility explains why peppers (new growth) are affected differently. Clarify: Tomato's lower leaf symptoms usually mean it needs Potassium or Magnesium as much as any P/N boost since N moves down.",
      "answer": "Pepper (New leaves yellow): High N needed to fix deficiency affecting new tissue immediately.\nTomato (Old leaf edges/purple veins): Often indicates Phosphorus limitation causing purple undersides, requiring balanced but leaner Nitrogen while boosting available Phos for root expansion in containers.",
      "- Distinguishes between symptom on 'new' vs 'old' leaves to prioritize N/P/K logic correctly.\n- Provides specific P or Mg needs context rather than just generic \"add fertilizer\" advice."
    },
    {
      "prompt": "**Scenario:** You are mid-summer and your strawberry beds show white spots where water hits, with yellowing around the edges. Your soil pH is 6.4.\n**Task:** Propose an amendment that specifically targets iron availability for strawberries without altering pH drastically. Explain why standard Nitrogen fertilizer would be a mistake here.",
      "answer": "Apply chelated Iron (Fe-EDDHA or Fe-DTPA) or elemental sulfur if you must lower pH slightly; avoid straight nitrate amendments which exacerbate micronutrient lockout in high organic matter soil common with strawberries. Standard Nitrogen boosts vegetative growth but ignores the iron deficiency causing yellowing spots, potentially making leaves more vulnerable to sunburn and disease stress.",
      "rubric": "- Correctly identifies Iron (Fe) availability issue specific to strawberries.\n- Suggests chelated forms or pH management rather than generic NPK boosters.\n\n"
    }
  ],
  "note": null,
  "intervention": null
}

